[[File:Conrad Bonnevie-Svendsen.jpg|thumb|upright|Conrad Bonnevie-Svendsen at the [[Rotary International]] 1949&ndash;50 Board of Directors.]]
'''Conrad Bonnevie-Svendsen''' (11 April 1898 &ndash; 12 June 1983) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] priest and government minister.<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Conrad Bonnevie-Svendsen|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo|editor=Henriksen, Petter|url=http://www.snl.no/Conrad_Bonnevie-Svendsen|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2010-05-19}}</ref> His father was Conrad Svendsen, Norway's first priest for the deaf.<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Conrad Bonnevie-Svendsen |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Thorleiv |last=Austad |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Conrad_Bonnevie-Svendsen/utdypning |language=Norwegian |accessdate=02 February 2010 }}</ref> Conrad the son worked at his father's school for deaf at [[Nordstrand, Norway|Nordstrand]] while studying theology at the university, and eventually took over his father's leadership of the school. During the [[German occupation of Norway]] in [[World War II]], he helped organise the [[Norwegian resistance movement|resistance]], and had to flee to [[Sweden]] towards the end of the war.<ref name=nbl/>

After the war, [[Einar Gerhardsen]] formed an interim [[Einar Gerhardsen's first term as Prime Minister of Norway|coalition government]] lasting from 25 June till 5 November.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/the-structure-of-the-registry/governments/modern-times/governments-since-1945/einar-gerhardsens-first-government-1945.html?id=438716|title=Einar Gerhardsen's First Government|publisher=Government.no|accessdate=2010-05-19}}</ref> Bonnevie-Svendsen was appointed consultative Minister of Education and Church Affairs, representing ''Hjemmefronten'' (the [[Norwegian resistance movement]]).<ref name=B>{{cite web|url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/the-structure-of-the-registry/alphabetical-register/b.html?id=410100|title=Det norske statsr<U+00E5>d 1814-: III Personer 1814-|publisher=Government.no|accessdate=2010-05-19}}</ref> He later helped found the organisation now known as [[Norwegian Church Aid]].<ref name=nbl/> He became vice president of [[Rotary International]] in 1949, and in 1952 he was made honorary doctor at the [[University of Kiel]].<ref name=snl/><ref name=nbl/>

